Row-Level Export Hooks - Modify entire row of data for specific channels:

REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: Dynamic availability_date based on stock status (Google Shopping - WordPress Standards):

<?php
/**
 * Modify availability_date for Google Shopping based on product stock status.
 *
 * @param array $row Product data row.
 * @param WC_Product|WC_Product_Variation $product Product object.
 * @return array Modified product row.
 */
add_filter(
	'wt_batch_product_export_row_data_google',
	function( $row, $product ) {
		if ( ! isset( $row['availability_date'] ) ) {
			return $row;
		}

		$stock_status = $product->get_stock_status();

		if ( 'onbackorder' === $stock_status ) {
			// Set to current date + 14 days for backorder
			$row['availability_date'] = gmdate( 'c', strtotime( '+14 days' ) );
		} elseif ( 'instock' === $stock_status ) {
			// Leave empty for in-stock items
			$row['availability_date'] = '';
		}

		return $row;
	},
	10,
	2
);
?>

Hook Pattern: wt_batch_product_export_row_data_{channel}

Available for all channels (google, facebook, pinterest, tiktok, bing, twitter, etc.)

Parameters:
- $row (array): Complete row data with all mapped fields
- $product (WC_Product|WC_Product_Variation): Product object

Use Cases:
- Conditional field values based on product properties
- Complex pricing or date logic
- Dynamic modifications across multiple fields
- Stock status-based calculations

Twitter/X Row-Level Export Hook:

Hook: wt_batch_product_export_row_data_twitter

Description: Modify entire row of product data for Twitter/X feed before export. This hook runs for each product variation/product and allows you to dynamically adjust all feed fields.

Example: Custom availability handling for Twitter feed:

add_filter('wt_batch_product_export_row_data_twitter', function($row, $product) {
    if (!isset($row['availability_date'])) {
        return $row;
    }

    $stock_status = $product->get_stock_status();
    if ('onbackorder' === $stock_status) {
        // Set to current date + 14 days for backorder
        $row['availability_date'] = gmdate('c', strtotime('+14 days'));
    } elseif ('instock' === $stock_status) {
        // Leave empty for in-stock
        $row['availability_date'] = '';
    }

    return $row;
}, 10, 2);

Parameters:
- $row (array): Complete row data with all mapped fields for Twitter feed
- $product (WC_Product|WC_Product_Variation): Product object

Return: Modified $row array

Use Cases:
- Conditional field values based on product properties
- Custom pricing or date logic for Twitter/X platform
- Stock status-based calculations
- Platform-specific field adjustments

WebToffee: Complete Meta Shops Integration (Feed + Frontend)

META SHOPS REQUIREMENT:
Meta Shops expects checkout URLs in: https://example.com/checkout/?products=PRODUCT_ID
But WooCommerce doesn't natively handle this ?products= parameter.

SOLUTION: Two-part integration
1. Customize FEED URLs using WebToffee hooks
2. Handle FRONTEND requests using WordPress hooks

================================================================================
PART 1: Feed URL Customization (WebToffee Hook)
================================================================================

HOOK: wt_feed_facebook_product_checkout_link

<?php
add_filter(
    'wt_feed_facebook_product_checkout_link',
    function( $checkout_url, $product ) {
        $product_id = $product->get_id();
        if ( ! $product_id ) {
            return $checkout_url;
        }
        $checkout_base = trailingslashit( wc_get_checkout_url() );
        $meta_checkout_url = $checkout_base . '?products=' . intval( $product_id );
        return esc_url( $meta_checkout_url );
    },
    10,
    2
);
?>

RESULT: Feed exports URLs like: https://example.com/checkout/?products=123

================================================================================
PART 2: Frontend Handler (WordPress Template Redirect Hook)
================================================================================

HOOK: template_redirect (WordPress core hook)

This code detects incoming ?products= requests and adds items to cart:

<?php
add_action( 'template_redirect', function() {
    // Check if products parameter exists
    if ( ! isset( $_GET['products'] ) ) {
        return;
    }

    // Get and sanitize product IDs
    $product_ids = sanitize_text_field( $_GET['products'] );
    if ( empty( $product_ids ) ) {
        return;
    }

    // Parse multiple products if comma-separated
    $product_array = array_filter( array_map( 'intval', explode( ',', $product_ids ) ) );
    if ( empty( $product_array ) ) {
        return;
    }

    // Add products to cart
    foreach ( $product_array as $product_id ) {
        if ( wc_get_product( $product_id ) ) {
            WC()->cart->add_to_cart( $product_id, 1 );
        }
    }

    // Redirect to checkout
    wp_redirect( wc_get_checkout_url() );
    exit;
}, 20 );
?>

WHAT THIS DOES:
- Detects ?products=123 (or ?products=123,456,789)
- Adds each product to WooCommerce cart
- Redirects to checkout page
- User completes purchase

================================================================================
COMPLETE FLOW:
================================================================================

1. Meta Shops exports URL: https://example.com/checkout/?products=123
2. User clicks checkout
3. PART 2 code detects parameter, adds product to cart
4. User redirected to: https://example.com/checkout/
5. Standard WooCommerce checkout appears
6. Payment processed normally

================================================================================
INSTALLATION:
================================================================================

- PART 1 code: Add to functions.php or custom plugin
- PART 2 code: Add to functions.php or custom plugin (same file is fine)
- Both are required for complete Meta Shops integration
- Test before going live

CHANNEL VARIATIONS:
- For Google: Change wt_feed_facebook_product_checkout_link to wt_feed_google_product_checkout_link
- For Pinterest: Change to wt_feed_pinterest_product_checkout_link
- Part 2 works for ALL channels that export ?products= format

